<edge source="concept.caution" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.caution.integral_part_of.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.caution.integral_part_of.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.caution</data>
  <data key="d9">Caution</data>
  <data key="d10">prudence_part</data>
  <data key="d11">integral_part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">virtue</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q048-a001-resp-concept-caution-integral-part-of-concept-prudence</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q048.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 11): "Of such things one needs to have the sense, and this is understanding." Of these eight, five belong to prudence as a cognitive virtue , namely, " memory ," "reasoning," "understanding," "docility" and "shrewdness": while the three others belong thereto, as commanding and applying knowledge to action, namely, "foresight," "circumspection" and "caution." The reason of their difference is seen from the fact that three things may be observed in reference to knowledge</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20">integral</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.caution" target="st.ii-ii.q048.a001" id="edge.concept.caution.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q048.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.caution.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q048.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.caution</data>
  <data key="d9">Caution</data>
  <data key="d10">prudence_part</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q048.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.48 a.1 — The three parts of prudence: integral, subjective, and potential</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q048-a001-resp-concept-caution-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q048-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q048.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 11): "Of such things one needs to have the sense, and this is understanding." Of these eight, five belong to prudence as a cognitive virtue , namely, " memory ," "reasoning," "understanding," "docility" and "shrewdness": while the three others belong thereto, as commanding and applying knowledge to action, namely, "foresight," "circumspection" and "caution." The reason of their difference is seen from the fact that three things may be observed in reference to knowledge</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.caution" target="st.ii-ii.q049.a008" id="edge.concept.caution.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a008">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.caution.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.caution</data>
  <data key="d9">Caution</data>
  <data key="d10">prudence_part</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049.a008</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 a.8 — Caution</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q049-a008-resp-concept-caution-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q049-a008</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore prudence needs caution, so that we may have such a grasp of good as to avoid evil .</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
