</edge>
<edge source="concept.circumspection" target="st.ii-ii.q049.a007" id="edge.concept.circumspection.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a007">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.circumspection.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.circumspection</data>
  <data key="d9">Circumspection</data>
  <data key="d10">prudence_part</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049.a007</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 a.7 — Circumspection</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q049-a007-resp-concept-circumspection-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q049-a007</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence the need of circumspection in prudence , viz</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.command" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a008" id="edge.concept.command.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a008">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.command.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.command</data>
  <data key="d9">Command</data>
  <data key="d10">act</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a008</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.8 — Is its proper act command?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a008-resp-concept-command-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a008</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But the practical reason, which is directed to action, goes further, and its third act is "to command," which act consists in applying to action the things counselled and judged</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.common_good" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a010" id="edge.concept.common_good.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a010">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.common_good.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a010</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.common_good</data>
  <data key="d9">Common Good</data>
  <data key="d10">end</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a010</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.10 — Does prudence extend to the governing of many?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a010-resp-concept-common-good-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a010</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 8) some have held that prudence does not extend to the common good , but only to the good of the individual , and this because they thought that man is not bound to seek other than his own good</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.common_good" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a011" id="edge.concept.common_good.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a011">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.common_good.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a011</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.common_good</data>
  <data key="d9">Common Good</data>
  <data key="d10">end</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a011</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.11 — Is the prudence which regards private good the same in species as that which regards the common good?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a011-resp-concept-common-good-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a011</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">another, "domestic prudence " which is directed to the common good of the home</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.counsel_gift" target="concept.mercy_beatitude" id="edge.concept.counsel_gift.corresponds_to.concept.mercy_beatitude">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.counsel_gift.corresponds_to.concept.mercy_beatitude</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.counsel_gift</data>
  <data key="d9">Gift of Counsel</data>
  <data key="d10">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d11">corresponds_to</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.mercy_beatitude</data>
  <data key="d13">Beatitude of Mercy</data>
  <data key="d14">beatitude</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q052-a004-resp-concept-counsel-gift-corresponds-to-concept-mercy-beatitude</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q052.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">see note on II-II:30:1 is profitable to all things." Therefore the beatitude of mercy specially corresponds to the gift of counsel, not as eliciting but as directing mercy.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.counsel_gift" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.counsel_gift.corresponds_to.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.counsel_gift.corresponds_to.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.counsel_gift</data>
  <data key="d9">Gift of Counsel</data>
  <data key="d10">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d11">corresponds_to</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">virtue</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q052-a002-resp-concept-counsel-gift-corresponds-to-concept-prudence</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q052.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Therefore the gift of counsel corresponds to prudence , as helping and perfecting it.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.counsel_gift" target="st.ii-ii.q052.a001" id="edge.concept.counsel_gift.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q052.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.counsel_gift.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q052.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.counsel_gift</data>
  <data key="d9">Gift of Counsel</data>
  <data key="d10">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q052.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.52 a.1 — Should counsel be reckoned among the seven gifts of the Holy Ghost?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q052-a001-resp-concept-counsel-gift-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q052-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q052.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Again, it is proper to the rational creature to be moved through the research of reason to perform any particular action, and this research is called counsel</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.counsel_gift" target="st.ii-ii.q052.a002" id="edge.concept.counsel_gift.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q052.a002">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.counsel_gift.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q052.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.counsel_gift</data>
  <data key="d9">Gift of Counsel</data>
  <data key="d10">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q052.a002</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.52 a.2 — Does the gift of counsel correspond to prudence?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q052-a002-resp-concept-counsel-gift-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q052-a002</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q052.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Consequently prudence , which denotes rectitude of reason , is chiefly perfected and helped through being ruled and moved by the Holy Ghost , and this belongs to the gift of counsel, as stated above ( Article 1 )</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.counsel_gift" target="st.ii-ii.q052.a003" id="edge.concept.counsel_gift.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q052.a003">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.counsel_gift.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q052.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.counsel_gift</data>
  <data key="d9">Gift of Counsel</data>
  <data key="d10">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q052.a003</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.52 a.3 — Does the gift of counsel remain in heaven?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q052-a003-resp-concept-counsel-gift-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q052-a003</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q052.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">v, 19) "the angels take counsel of God about things beneath them": wherefore the instruction which they receive from God in such matters is called "counsel." Accordingly the gift of counsel is in the blessed, in so far as God preserves in them the knowledge that they have, and enlightens them in their nescience of what has to be done.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.counsel_gift" target="st.ii-ii.q052.a004" id="edge.concept.counsel_gift.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q052.a004">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.counsel_gift.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q052.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.counsel_gift</data>
  <data key="d9">Gift of Counsel</data>
  <data key="d10">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q052.a004</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.52 a.4 — Does the fifth beatitude, "Blessed are the merciful," etc. correspond to the gift of counsel?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q052-a004-resp-concept-counsel-gift-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q052-a004</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q052.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence such things as are of most use for an end, should above all correspond to the gift of counsel</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.covetousness" target="st.ii-ii.q055.a008" id="edge.concept.covetousness.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a008">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.covetousness.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d9">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055.a008</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 a.8 — The origin of these vices</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a008-resp-concept-covetousness-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q055-a008</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence the undue use of reason appears chiefly in the vices opposed to justice , the chief of which is covetousness</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.craftiness" target="concept.covetousness" id="edge.concept.craftiness.caused_by.concept.covetousness">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.craftiness.caused_by.concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.craftiness</data>
  <data key="d9">Craftiness</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">caused_by</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d13">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d14">vice</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a008-resp-concept-craftiness-caused-by-concept-covetousness</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Therefore the aforesaid vices arise chiefly from covetousness .</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.craftiness" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.craftiness.opposed_by.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.craftiness.opposed_by.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.craftiness</data>
  <data key="d9">Craftiness</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">opposed_by</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">virtue</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a003-resp-concept-craftiness-opposed-by-concept-prudence</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">This is consequently a sin opposed to prudence , and distinct from prudence of the flesh.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.craftiness" target="st.ii-ii.q055.a003" id="edge.concept.craftiness.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a003">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.craftiness.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.craftiness</data>
  <data key="d9">Craftiness</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055.a003</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 a.3 — Is craftiness a special sin?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a003-resp-concept-craftiness-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q055-a003</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">secondly, when, in order to obtain a certain end, whether good or evil , a man uses means that are not true but fictitious and counterfeit, and this belongs to the sin of craftiness</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
