  <data key="d8">concept.craftiness</data>
  <data key="d9">Craftiness</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055.a008</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 a.8 — The origin of these vices</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a008-resp-concept-craftiness-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q055-a008</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">II-II:47:13 ), carnal prudence and craftiness, as well as guile and fraud , bear a certain resemblance to prudence in some kind of use of the reason</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.craftiness" target="st.ii-ii.q056.a002" id="edge.concept.craftiness.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q056.a002">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.craftiness.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q056.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.craftiness</data>
  <data key="d9">Craftiness</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q056.a002</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.56 a.2 — The precepts relating to the opposite vices</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q056-a002-resp-concept-craftiness-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q056-a002</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q056.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now craftiness, as to its execution, is committed chiefly in matters of justice , as stated above ( II-II:55:8 ): and so it was fitting that the Law should contain precepts forbidding the execution of craftiness, in so far as this pertains to injustice , as when a man uses guile and fraud in calumniating another or in stealing his goods.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.docility" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.docility.integral_part_of.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.docility.integral_part_of.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.docility</data>
  <data key="d9">Docility</data>
  <data key="d10">prudence_part</data>
  <data key="d11">integral_part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">virtue</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q048-a001-resp-concept-docility-integral-part-of-concept-prudence</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q048.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 11): "Of such things one needs to have the sense, and this is understanding." Of these eight, five belong to prudence as a cognitive virtue , namely, " memory ," "reasoning," "understanding," "docility" and "shrewdness": while the three others belong thereto, as commanding and applying knowledge to action, namely, "foresight," "circumspection" and "caution." The reason of their difference is seen from the fact that three things may be observed in reference to knowledge</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20">integral</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.docility" target="st.ii-ii.q048.a001" id="edge.concept.docility.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q048.a001">
