  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049.a003</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 a.3 — Docility</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q049-a003-resp-concept-docility-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q049-a003</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">the old men), "that are wise, and join thyself from thy heart to their wisdom." Now it is a mark of docility to be ready to be taught: and consequently docility is fittingly reckoned a part of prudence</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.domestic_prudence" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.domestic_prudence.subjective_part_of.concept.prudence">
