  <data key="d9">Fraud</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055.a008</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 a.8 — The origin of these vices</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a008-resp-concept-fraud-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q055-a008</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">II-II:47:13 ), carnal prudence and craftiness, as well as guile and fraud , bear a certain resemblance to prudence in some kind of use of the reason</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.future_solicitude" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.future_solicitude.contrary_to.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.future_solicitude.contrary_to.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.future_solicitude</data>
  <data key="d9">Solicitude about the Future</data>
  <data key="d10">defect</data>
  <data key="d11">contrary_to</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">virtue</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a007-resp-concept-future-solicitude-contrary-to-concept-prudence</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence Our Lord forbids such like excessive solicitude, saying: "Be . . . not solicitous for tomorrow," wherefore He adds, "for the morrow will be solicitous for itself," that is to say, the morrow will have its own solicitude, which will be burden enough for the soul</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.future_solicitude" target="st.ii-ii.q055.a007" id="edge.concept.future_solicitude.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a007">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.future_solicitude.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.future_solicitude</data>
  <data key="d9">Solicitude about the Future</data>
  <data key="d10">defect</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055.a007</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 a.7 — Solicitude about the future</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a007-resp-concept-future-solicitude-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q055-a007</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">not solicitous for tomorrow," wherefore He adds, "for the morrow will be solicitous for itself," that is to say, the morrow will have its own solicitude, which will be burden enough for the soul</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.gnome" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.gnome.potential_part_of.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.gnome.potential_part_of.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.gnome</data>
  <data key="d9">Gnome</data>
  <data key="d10">prudence_part</data>
  <data key="d11">potential_part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">virtue</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q048-a001-resp-concept-gnome-potential-part-of-concept-prudence</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q048.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">On this way the parts of prudence are " good counsel," which concerns counsel, "synesis," which concerns judgment in matters of ordinary occurrence, and "gnome," which concerns judgment in matters of exception to the law : while " prudence " is about the chief act, viz</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20">potential</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.gnome" target="st.ii-ii.q048.a001" id="edge.concept.gnome.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q048.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.gnome.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q048.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.gnome</data>
  <data key="d9">Gnome</data>
  <data key="d10">prudence_part</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q048.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.48 a.1 — The three parts of prudence: integral, subjective, and potential</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q048-a001-resp-concept-gnome-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q048-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q048.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">On this way the parts of prudence are " good counsel," which concerns counsel, "synesis," which concerns judgment in matters of ordinary occurrence, and "gnome," which concerns judgment in matters of exception to the law : while " prudence " is about the chief act, viz</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.gnome" target="st.ii-ii.q051.a004" id="edge.concept.gnome.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q051.a004">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.gnome.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q051.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.gnome</data>
  <data key="d9">Gnome</data>
  <data key="d10">prudence_part</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q051.a004</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.51 a.4 — Is gnome a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q051-a004-resp-concept-gnome-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q051-a004</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q051.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence it is necessary to judge of such matters according to higher principles than the common laws, according to which synesis (judging according to common law ) judges: and corresponding to such higher principles it is necessary to have a higher virtue of judgment, which is called gnome (judging according to general law ), and which denotes a certain discrimination in judgment.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.guile" target="concept.covetousness" id="edge.concept.guile.caused_by.concept.covetousness">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.guile.caused_by.concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.guile</data>
  <data key="d9">Guile</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">caused_by</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d13">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d14">vice</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a008-resp-concept-guile-caused-by-concept-covetousness</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Therefore the aforesaid vices arise chiefly from covetousness .</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.guile" target="concept.craftiness" id="edge.concept.guile.caused_by.concept.craftiness">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.guile.caused_by.concept.craftiness</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.guile</data>
  <data key="d9">Guile</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">caused_by</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.craftiness</data>
  <data key="d13">Craftiness</data>
  <data key="d14">vice</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a004-resp-concept-guile-caused-by-concept-craftiness</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence guile denotes a certain execution of craftiness, and accordingly belongs thereto.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
