<edge source="concept.imprudence" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.imprudence.opposed_by.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.imprudence.opposed_by.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.imprudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">opposed_by</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">virtue</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a001-resp-concept-imprudence-opposed-by-concept-prudence</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d18">Taken as a privation, imprudence denotes lack of that prudence which a man can and ought to have, and in this sense imprudence is a sin by reason of a man's negligence in striving to have prudence</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.imprudence" target="st.ii-ii.q053.a001" id="edge.concept.imprudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.imprudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.imprudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 a.1 — Is imprudence a sin?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a001-resp-concept-imprudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q053-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Imprudence may be taken in two ways, first, as a privation, secondly, as a contrary</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.imprudence" target="st.ii-ii.q053.a002" id="edge.concept.imprudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a002">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.imprudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.imprudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053.a002</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 a.2 — Is it a special sin?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a002-resp-concept-imprudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q053-a002</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">On the first way, a vice may be said to be general on two counts: first, essentially , because it is predicated of all sins : and in this way imprudence is not a general sin , as neither is prudence a general virtue : since it is concerned with special acts, namely the very acts of reason: secondly, by participation</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.imprudence" target="st.ii-ii.q053.a003" id="edge.concept.imprudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a003">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.imprudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.imprudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053.a003</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 a.3 — Precipitation or temerity</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a003-resp-concept-imprudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q053-a003</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Since then inordinate counsel pertains to imprudence, it is evident that the vice of precipitation is contained under imprudence.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.imprudence" target="st.ii-ii.q053.a004" id="edge.concept.imprudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a004">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.imprudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.imprudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053.a004</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 a.4 — Thoughtlessness</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a004-resp-concept-imprudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q053-a004</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d18">Thought signifies the act of the intellect in considering the truth about. something. Now just as research belongs to the reason, so judgment belongs to the intellect . Wherefore in speculative matters a demonstrative science is said to exercise judgment, in s</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.imprudence" target="st.ii-ii.q053.a005" id="edge.concept.imprudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a005">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.imprudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.imprudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053.a005</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 a.5 — Inconstancy</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a005-resp-concept-imprudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q053-a005</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now just as all rectitude of the practical reason belongs in some degree to prudence , so all lack of that rectitude belongs to imprudence</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.imprudence" target="st.ii-ii.q053.a006" id="edge.concept.imprudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a006">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.imprudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.imprudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053.a006</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 a.6 — The origin of these vices</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a006-resp-concept-imprudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q053-a006</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d18">As the Philosopher states (Ethic. vi, 5) "pleasure above all corrupts the estimate of prudence ," and chiefly sexual pleasure which absorbs the mind , and draws it to sensible delight. Now the perfection of prudence and of every intellectual virtue consists in</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.inconstancy" target="concept.lust" id="edge.concept.inconstancy.caused_by.concept.lust">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.inconstancy.caused_by.concept.lust</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.inconstancy</data>
  <data key="d9">Inconstancy</data>
  <data key="d10">defect</data>
  <data key="d11">caused_by</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.lust</data>
  <data key="d13">Lust</data>
  <data key="d14">vice</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a006-resp-concept-inconstancy-caused-by-concept-lust</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore, since the aforesaid vices involve a defect of prudence and of the practical reason, as stated above (Articles 2 and 5 ), it follows that they arise chiefly from lust .</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.inconstancy" target="concept.command" id="edge.concept.inconstancy.contrary_to.concept.command">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.inconstancy.contrary_to.concept.command</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.inconstancy</data>
  <data key="d9">Inconstancy</data>
  <data key="d10">defect</data>
  <data key="d11">contrary_to</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.command</data>
  <data key="d13">Command</data>
  <data key="d14">act</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a005-resp-concept-inconstancy-contrary-to-concept-command</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">And just as precipitation is due to a defect in the act of counsel, and thoughtlessness to a defect in the act of judgment, so inconstancy arises from a defect in the act of command</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.inconstancy" target="concept.imprudence" id="edge.concept.inconstancy.species_of.concept.imprudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.inconstancy.species_of.concept.imprudence</data>
