  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q054.a003</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.54 a.3 — Is negligence a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q054-a003-resp-concept-negligence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q054-a003</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q054.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 2, Reply to Objection 3 ), negligence arises out of a certain remissness of the will , the result being a lack of solicitude on the part of the reason in commanding what it should command, or as it should command</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.political_prudence" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.political_prudence.subjective_part_of.concept.prudence">
