  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a002</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.2 — If in the reason, is it only in the practical, or also in the speculative reason?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a002-resp-concept-practical-reason-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a002</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 5) "a prudent man is one who is capable of taking good counsel." Now counsel is about things that we have to do in relation to some end: and the reason that deals with things to be done for an end is the practical reason</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
