  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.precipitation" target="concept.imprudence" id="edge.concept.precipitation.species_of.concept.imprudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.precipitation.species_of.concept.imprudence</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.precipitation</data>
  <data key="d9">Precipitation or Temerity</data>
  <data key="d10">defect</data>
  <data key="d11">species_of</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.imprudence</data>
  <data key="d13">Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d14">vice</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a003-resp-concept-precipitation-species-of-concept-imprudence</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Since then inordinate counsel pertains to imprudence, it is evident that the vice of precipitation is contained under imprudence.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.precipitation" target="st.ii-ii.q053.a003" id="edge.concept.precipitation.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a003">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.precipitation.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.precipitation</data>
  <data key="d9">Precipitation or Temerity</data>
  <data key="d10">defect</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053.a003</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 a.3 — Precipitation or temerity</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a003-resp-concept-precipitation-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q053-a003</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Precipitation is ascribed metaphorically to acts of the soul , by way of similitude to bodily movement</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="concept.common_good" id="edge.concept.prudence.directed_to.concept.common_good">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.directed_to.concept.common_good</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">directed_to</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.common_good</data>
  <data key="d13">Common Good</data>
  <data key="d14">end</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a010-resp-concept-prudence-directed-to-concept-common-good</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 8) some have held that prudence does not extend to the common good , but only to the good of the individual , and this because they thought that man is not bound to seek other than his own good</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="concept.command" id="edge.concept.prudence.has_act.concept.command">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.has_act.concept.command</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">has_act</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.command</data>
  <data key="d13">Command</data>
  <data key="d14">act</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a008-resp-concept-prudence-has-act-concept-command</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence that which is the chief act of reason in regard to action must needs be the chief act of prudence</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="concept.solicitude" id="edge.concept.prudence.has_act.concept.solicitude">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.has_act.concept.solicitude</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">has_act</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.solicitude</data>
  <data key="d13">Solicitude</data>
  <data key="d14">act</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a009-resp-concept-prudence-has-act-concept-solicitude</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now this belongs to prudence , whose chief act is a command about what has been already counselled and judged in matters of action</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="concept.counsel_gift" id="edge.concept.prudence.perfected_by.concept.counsel_gift">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.perfected_by.concept.counsel_gift</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">perfected_by</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.counsel_gift</data>
  <data key="d13">Gift of Counsel</data>
  <data key="d14">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q052-a002-resp-concept-prudence-perfected-by-concept-counsel-gift</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q052.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Consequently prudence , which denotes rectitude of reason , is chiefly perfected and helped through being ruled and moved by the Holy Ghost , and this belongs to the gift of counsel, as stated above ( Article 1 )</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="concept.practical_reason" id="edge.concept.prudence.resides_in.concept.practical_reason">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.resides_in.concept.practical_reason</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">resides_in</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.practical_reason</data>
  <data key="d13">Practical Reason</data>
  <data key="d14">faculty</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a002-resp-concept-prudence-resides-in-concept-practical-reason</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence it is evident that prudence resides only in the practical reason.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="concept.reason_faculty" id="edge.concept.prudence.resides_in.concept.reason_faculty">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.resides_in.concept.reason_faculty</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">resides_in</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.reason_faculty</data>
  <data key="d13">Reason</data>
  <data key="d14">faculty</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a001-resp-concept-prudence-resides-in-concept-reason-faculty</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore it is manifest that prudence belongs directly to the cognitive, and not to the sensitive faculty, because by the latter we know nothing but what is within reach and offers itself to the senses: while to obtain knowledge of the future from knowledge of the present or past, which pertains to prudence , belongs properly to the reason, because this is done by a process of comparison</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a001" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.1 — Is prudence in the will or in the reason?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a001-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore it is manifest that prudence belongs directly to the cognitive, and not to the sensitive faculty, because by the latter we know nothing but what is within reach and offers itself to the senses: while to obtain knowledge of the future from knowledge of the present or past, which pertains to prudence , belongs properly to the reason, because this is done by a process of comparison</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a002" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a002">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a002</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.2 — If in the reason, is it only in the practical, or also in the speculative reason?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a002-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a002</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence it is evident that prudence resides only in the practical reason.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a003" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a003">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a003</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.3 — Does it take cognizance of singulars?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a003-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a003</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1, Reply to Objection 3 ), to prudence belongs not only the consideration of the reason, but also the application to action, which is the end of the practical reason</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a004" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a004">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a004</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.4 — Is it virtue?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a004-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a004</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now it belongs to prudence , as stated above ( Article 1, Reply to Objection 3</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a005" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a005">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a005</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.5 — Is it a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a005-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a005</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Accordingly we must say that since prudence is in the reason, as stated above ( Article 2 ), it is differentiated from the other intellectual virtues by a material difference of objects</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a006" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a006">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a006</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.6 — Does it appoint the end to the moral virtues?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a006-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a006</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">About these is prudence , which applies universal principles to the particular conclusions of practical matters</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a007" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a007">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a007</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.7 — Does it fix the mean in the moral virtues?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a007-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a007</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But it belongs to the ruling of prudence to decide in what manner and by what means man shall obtain the mean of reason in his deeds</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a008" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a008">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a008</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.8 — Is its proper act command?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a008-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a008</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is "right reason applied to action," as stated above ( Article 2 )</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a009" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a009">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a009</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a009</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.9 — Does solicitude or watchfulness belong to prudence?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a009-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a009</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now this belongs to prudence , whose chief act is a command about what has been already counselled and judged in matters of action</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a010" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a010">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a010</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a010</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.10 — Does prudence extend to the governing of many?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a010-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a010</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 8) some have held that prudence does not extend to the common good , but only to the good of the individual , and this because they thought that man is not bound to seek other than his own good</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a011" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a011">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a011</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a011</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.11 — Is the prudence which regards private good the same in species as that which regards the common good?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a011-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a011</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore there must needs be different species of prudence corresponding to these different ends, so that one is " prudence " simply so called, which is directed to one's own good</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a012" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a012">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a012</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a012</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.12 — Is prudence in subjects, or only in their rulers?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a012-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a012</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a012.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is in the reason</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a013" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a013">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a013</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a013</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.13 — Is prudence in the wicked?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a013-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a013</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a013.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is threefold</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a014" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a014">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a014</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a014</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.14 — Is prudence in all good men?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a014-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a014</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a014.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now whoever has grace has charity , so that he must needs have all the other virtues , and hence, since prudence is a virtue , as shown above ( Article 4 ), he must, of necessity , have prudence also.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a015" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a015">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a015</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a015</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.15 — Is prudence in us naturally?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a015-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a015</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a015.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As shown above ( Article 3 ), prudence includes knowledge both of universals, and of the singular matters of action to which prudence applies the universal principles</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a016" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a016">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a016</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a016</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.16 — Is prudence lost by forgetfulness?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a016-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a016</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a016.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But prudence consists not in knowledge alone, but also in an act of the appetite , because as stated above ( Article 8 ), its principal act is one of command, whereby a man applies the knowledge he has, to the purpose of appetition and operation</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q048.a001" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q048.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q048.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q048.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.48 a.1 — The three parts of prudence: integral, subjective, and potential</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q048-a001-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q048-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q048.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">On this way, out of all the things mentioned above, eight may be taken as parts of prudence , namely, the six assigned by Macrobius</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q049.a001" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 a.1 — Memory</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q049-a001-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q049-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence regards contingent matters of action, as stated above ( II-II:47:5 )</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q049.a002" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a002">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049.a002</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 a.2 — Understanding or Intelligence</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q049-a002-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q049-a002</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Therefore since prudence is right reason applied to action, the whole process of prudence must needs have its source in understanding</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q049.a003" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a003">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049.a003</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 a.3 — Docility</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q049-a003-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q049-a003</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">II-II:47:3 ) prudence is concerned with particular matters of action, and since such matters are of infinite variety, no one man can consider them all sufficiently</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q049.a004" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a004">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049.a004</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 a.4 — Shrewdness</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q049-a004-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q049-a004</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence consists in a right estimate about matters of action</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q049.a005" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a005">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049.a005</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 a.5 — Reason</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q049-a005-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q049-a005</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">The work of prudence is to take good counsel, as stated in Ethic</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q049.a006" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a006">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049.a006</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 a.6 — foresight</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q049-a006-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q049-a006</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( 47, 1, ad 2, 6,13 ), prudence is properly about the means to an end, and its proper work is to set them in due order to the end</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q049.a007" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a007">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049.a007</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 a.7 — Circumspection</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q049-a007-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q049-a007</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 6 ), it belongs to prudence chiefly to direct something aright to an end</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q049.a008" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a008">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049.a008</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 a.8 — Caution</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q049-a008-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q049-a008</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">The things with which prudence is concerned, are contingent matters of action, wherein, even as false is found with true , so is evil mingled with good , on account of the great variety of these matters of action, wherein good is often hindered by evil , and evil has the appearance of good</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q050.a001" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q050.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q050.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q050.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.50 a.1 — Is a species of prudence regnative?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q050-a001-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q050-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q050.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( II-II:47:10 ), it belongs to prudence to govern and command, so that wherever in human acts we find a special kind of governance and command, there must be a special kind of prudence</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q050.a002" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q050.a002">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q050.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q050.a002</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.50 a.2 — Is political economy a species of prudence?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q050-a002-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q050-a002</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q050.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">and to this belongs that species of prudence which is called political.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q050.a003" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q050.a003">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q050.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q050.a003</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.50 a.3 — Is domestic economy a species of prudence?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q050-a003-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q050-a003</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q050.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">And therefore, just as prudence commonly so called which governs the individual , is distinct from political prudence , so must domestic prudence be distinct from both.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q050.a004" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q050.a004">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q050.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q050.a004</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.50 a.4 — Is military prudence?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q050-a004-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q050-a004</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q050.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Therefore in those things also which are in accordance with reason, there should be not only "political" prudence , which disposes in a suitable manner such things as belong to the common good , but also a "military" prudence , whereby hostile attacks are repelled.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q051.a001" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q051.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q051.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q051.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.51 a.1 — Is euboulia a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q051-a001-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q051-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q051.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( II-II:47:4 ) the nature of a human virtue consists in making a human act good . Now among the acts of man , it is proper to him to take counsel, since this denotes a research of the reason about the actions he has to perform and whereof human</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q051.a002" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q051.a002">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q051.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q051.a002</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.51 a.2 — Is it a special virtue, distinct from prudence?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q051-a002-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q051-a002</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q051.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Consequently euboulia (deliberating well) which makes man take good counsel must needs be a distinct virtue from prudence , which makes man command well</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q051.a003" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q051.a003">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q051.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q051.a003</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.51 a.3 — Is synesis a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q051-a003-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q051-a003</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q051.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">synesis (judging well according to common law ) signifies a right judgment, not indeed about speculative matters, but about particular practical matters, about which also is prudence</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q051.a004" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q051.a004">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q051.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q051.a004</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.51 a.4 — Is gnome a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q051-a004-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q051-a004</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q051.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d18">cognitive habits differ according to higher and lower principles: thus in speculative matters wisdom considers higher principles than science does, and consequently is distinguished from it; and so must it be also in practical matters. Now it is evident that w</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q052.a002" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q052.a002">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q052.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q052.a002</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.52 a.2 — Does the gift of counsel correspond to prudence?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q052-a002-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q052-a002</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q052.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Consequently prudence , which denotes rectitude of reason , is chiefly perfected and helped through being ruled and moved by the Holy Ghost , and this belongs to the gift of counsel, as stated above ( Article 1 )</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q054.a002" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q054.a002">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q054.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q054.a002</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.54 a.2 — To which virtue is it opposed?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q054-a002-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q054-a002</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q054.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now solicitude pertains to the reason, and rectitude of solicitude to prudence</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q055.a001" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 a.1 — Is prudence of the flesh a sin?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a001-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q055-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( II-II:47:13 ), prudence regards things which are directed to the end of life as a whole</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q055.a003" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a003">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055.a003</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 a.3 — Is craftiness a special sin?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a003-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q055-a003</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is "right reason applied to action," just as science is "right reason applied to knowledge ." On speculative matters one may sin against rectitude of knowledge in two ways: in one way when the reason is led to a false conclusion that appears to be true</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q056.a001" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q056.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q056.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q056.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.56 a.1 — The precepts of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q056-a001-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q056-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q056.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Now prudence is not about the end, but about the means, as stated above ( II-II:47:6 )</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence" target="st.ii-ii.q056.a002" id="edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q056.a002">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q056.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">virtue</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q056.a002</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.56 a.2 — The precepts relating to the opposite vices</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q056-a002-resp-concept-prudence-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q056-a002</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q056.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1 ), justice , above all, regards the aspect of something due, which is a necessary condition for a precept, because justice tends to render that which is due to another, as we shall state further on ( II-II:58:2 . Now craftiness, as</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence_of_flesh" target="concept.covetousness" id="edge.concept.prudence_of_flesh.caused_by.concept.covetousness">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence_of_flesh.caused_by.concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence_of_flesh</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence of the Flesh</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">caused_by</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.covetousness</data>
  <data key="d13">Covetousness</data>
  <data key="d14">vice</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a008-resp-concept-prudence-of-flesh-caused-by-concept-covetousness</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Therefore the aforesaid vices arise chiefly from covetousness .</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence_of_flesh" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.prudence_of_flesh.opposed_by.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence_of_flesh.opposed_by.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence_of_flesh</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence of the Flesh</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">opposed_by</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">virtue</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a001-resp-concept-prudence-of-flesh-opposed-by-concept-prudence</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence prudence of the flesh signifies properly the prudence of a man who looks upon carnal goods as the last end of his life</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence_of_flesh" target="st.ii-ii.q055.a001" id="edge.concept.prudence_of_flesh.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence_of_flesh.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence_of_flesh</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence of the Flesh</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 a.1 — Is prudence of the flesh a sin?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a001-resp-concept-prudence-of-flesh-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q055-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Hence prudence of the flesh signifies properly the prudence of a man who looks upon carnal goods as the last end of his life</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence_of_flesh" target="st.ii-ii.q055.a002" id="edge.concept.prudence_of_flesh.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a002">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence_of_flesh.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence_of_flesh</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence of the Flesh</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055.a002</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 a.2 — Is it a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a002-resp-concept-prudence-of-flesh-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q055-a002</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Accordingly if prudence of the flesh be taken as corresponding to prudence in its absolute signification, so that a man place the last end of his whole life in the care of the flesh, it is a mortal sin , because he turns away from God by so doing, since he cannot have several last ends, as stated above ( I-II:01:5 )</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.prudence_of_flesh" target="st.ii-ii.q055.a008" id="edge.concept.prudence_of_flesh.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a008">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.prudence_of_flesh.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q055.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.prudence_of_flesh</data>
  <data key="d9">Prudence of the Flesh</data>
  <data key="d10">vice</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055.a008</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 a.8 — The origin of these vices</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q055-a008-resp-concept-prudence-of-flesh-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q055-a008</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">II-II:47:13 ), carnal prudence and craftiness, as well as guile and fraud , bear a certain resemblance to prudence in some kind of use of the reason</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.reason_faculty" target="st.ii-ii.q047.a001" id="edge.concept.reason_faculty.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.reason_faculty.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q047.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.reason_faculty</data>
  <data key="d9">Reason</data>
  <data key="d10">faculty</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.1 — Is prudence in the will or in the reason?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a001-resp-concept-reason-faculty-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore it is manifest that prudence belongs directly to the cognitive, and not to the sensitive faculty, because by the latter we know nothing but what is within reach and offers itself to the senses: while to obtain knowledge of the future from knowledge of the present or past, which pertains to prudence , belongs properly to the reason, because this is done by a process of comparison</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.reasoning" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.reasoning.integral_part_of.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.reasoning.integral_part_of.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.reasoning</data>
  <data key="d9">Reasoning</data>
  <data key="d10">prudence_part</data>
  <data key="d11">integral_part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">virtue</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q048-a001-resp-concept-reasoning-integral-part-of-concept-prudence</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q048.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 11): "Of such things one needs to have the sense, and this is understanding." Of these eight, five belong to prudence as a cognitive virtue , namely, " memory ," "reasoning," "understanding," "docility" and "shrewdness": while the three others belong thereto, as commanding and applying knowledge to action, namely, "foresight," "circumspection" and "caution." The reason of their difference is seen from the fact that three things may be observed in reference to knowledge</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20">integral</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.reasoning" target="st.ii-ii.q048.a001" id="edge.concept.reasoning.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q048.a001">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.reasoning.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q048.a001</data>
