  <data key="d10">prudence_part</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q048.a001</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.48 a.1 — The three parts of prudence: integral, subjective, and potential</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q048-a001-resp-concept-reasoning-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q048-a001</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q048.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 11): "Of such things one needs to have the sense, and this is understanding." Of these eight, five belong to prudence as a cognitive virtue , namely, " memory ," "reasoning," "understanding," "docility" and "shrewdness": while the three others belong thereto, as commanding and applying knowledge to action, namely, "foresight," "circumspection" and "caution." The reason of their difference is seen from the fact that three things may be observed in reference to knowledge</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.reasoning" target="st.ii-ii.q049.a005" id="edge.concept.reasoning.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a005">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.reasoning.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q049.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.reasoning</data>
  <data key="d9">Reasoning</data>
  <data key="d10">prudence_part</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049.a005</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 a.5 — Reason</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q049-a005-resp-concept-reasoning-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q049-a005</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">But this is the work of reason</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.regnative_prudence" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.regnative_prudence.subjective_part_of.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.regnative_prudence.subjective_part_of.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.regnative_prudence</data>
  <data key="d9">Regnative Prudence</data>
  <data key="d10">prudence_part</data>
  <data key="d11">subjective_part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">virtue</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q048-a001-resp-concept-regnative-prudence-subjective-part-of-concept-prudence | ann.st-ii-ii-q050-a001-resp-concept-regnative-prudence-subjective-part-of-concept-prudence</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q048.a001.resp | st.ii-ii.q050.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">such is the multitude of a home or family , and this is ruled by "domestic prudence ": and such again is the multitude of a city or kingdom, the ruling principle of which is "regnative prudence " in the ruler, and "political prudence ," simply so called, in the subjects | Hence prudence in its special and most perfect sense, belongs to a king who is charged with the government of a city or kingdom: for which reason a species of prudence is reckoned to be regnative.</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20">subjective</data>
</edge>
