  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047.a009</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 a.9 — Does solicitude or watchfulness belong to prudence?</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q047-a009-resp-concept-solicitude-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q047-a009</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">vi, 9) that "one should be quick in carrying out the counsel taken, but slow in taking counsel." Hence it is that solicitude belongs properly to prudence , and for this reason Augustine says (De Morib</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
