<edge source="concept.thoughtlessness" target="concept.lust" id="edge.concept.thoughtlessness.caused_by.concept.lust">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.thoughtlessness.caused_by.concept.lust</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.thoughtlessness</data>
  <data key="d9">Thoughtlessness</data>
  <data key="d10">defect</data>
  <data key="d11">caused_by</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.lust</data>
  <data key="d13">Lust</data>
  <data key="d14">vice</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a006-resp-concept-thoughtlessness-caused-by-concept-lust</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">Wherefore, since the aforesaid vices involve a defect of prudence and of the practical reason, as stated above (Articles 2 and 5 ), it follows that they arise chiefly from lust .</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.thoughtlessness" target="concept.prudence" id="edge.concept.thoughtlessness.opposed_by.concept.prudence">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.thoughtlessness.opposed_by.concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.thoughtlessness</data>
  <data key="d9">Thoughtlessness</data>
  <data key="d10">defect</data>
  <data key="d11">opposed_by</data>
  <data key="d12">concept.prudence</data>
  <data key="d13">Prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">virtue</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a004-resp-concept-thoughtlessness-opposed-by-concept-prudence</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">strong_textual_inference</data>
  <data key="d18">It is therefore evident that thoughtlessness is a sin .</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.thoughtlessness" target="st.ii-ii.q053.a004" id="edge.concept.thoughtlessness.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a004">
  <data key="d7">edge.concept.thoughtlessness.treated_in.st.ii-ii.q053.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">concept.thoughtlessness</data>
  <data key="d9">Thoughtlessness</data>
  <data key="d10">defect</data>
  <data key="d11">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053.a004</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 a.4 — Thoughtlessness</data>
  <data key="d14">article</data>
  <data key="d15">ann.st-ii-ii-q053-a004-resp-concept-thoughtlessness-treated-in-st-ii-ii-q053-a004</data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d18">and consequently the lack of right judgment belongs to the vice of thoughtlessness, in so far, to wit, as one fails to judge rightly through contempt or neglect of those things on which a right judgment depends</data>
  <data key="d19">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a001" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a001</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.1 — Is prudence in the will or in the reason?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As Isidore says (Etym. x): "A prudent man is one who sees as it were from afar, for his sight is keen, and he foresees the event of uncertainties." Now sight belongs not to the appetitive but to the cognitive faculty. Wh</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a002" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a002</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.2 — If in the reason, is it only in the practical, or also in the speculative reason?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">According to the Philosopher (Ethic. vi, 5) "a prudent man is one who is capable of taking good counsel." Now counsel is about things that we have to do in relation to some end: and the reason that deals with things to b</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a003" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a003</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.3 — Does it take cognizance of singulars?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1, Reply to Objection 3 ), to prudence belongs not only the consideration of the reason, but also the application to action, which is the end of the practical reason. But no man can conveniently</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a004" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a004</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.4 — Is it virtue?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( I-II:55:3 ; I-II:56:1 ) when we were treating of virtues in general, " virtue is that which makes its possessor good , and his work good likewise." Now good may be understood in a twofold sense: first, </data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a005" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a005.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a005.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a005</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.5 — Is it a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Since acts and habits take their species from their objects, as shown above ( I-II:01:3 ; I-II:18:2 ; I-II:54:2 ), any habit that has a corresponding special object, distinct from other objects, must needs be a special h</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a006" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a006.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a006.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a006</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.6 — Does it appoint the end to the moral virtues?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The end of moral virtues is human good . Now the good of the human soul is to be in accord with reason, as Dionysius declares (Div. Nom. iv). Wherefore the ends of moral virtue must of necessity pre-exist in the reason. </data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a007" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a007.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a007.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a007</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.7 — Does it fix the mean in the moral virtues?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The proper end of each moral virtue consists precisely in conformity with right reason. For temperance intends that man should not stray from reason for the sake of his concupiscences ; fortitude , that he should not str</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a008" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a008.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a008.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a008</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.8 — Is its proper act command?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is "right reason applied to action," as stated above ( Article 2 ). Hence that which is the chief act of reason in regard to action must needs be the chief act of prudence . Now there are three such acts. The fi</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a009" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a009.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a009.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a009</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.9 — Does solicitude or watchfulness belong to prudence?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">According to Isidore (Etym. x), a man is said to be solicitous through being shrewd [solers] and alert [citus], in so far as a man through a certain shrewdness of mind is on the alert to do whatever has to be done. Now t</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a010" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a010.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a010.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a010</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.10 — Does prudence extend to the governing of many?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">According to the Philosopher (Ethic. vi, 8) some have held that prudence does not extend to the common good , but only to the good of the individual , and this because they thought that man is not bound to seek other tha</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a011" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a011.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a011.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a011</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.11 — Is the prudence which regards private good the same in species as that which regards the common good?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 5 ; II-II:54:2 ad 1 ), the species of habits differ according to the difference of object considered in its formal aspect. Now the formal aspect of all things directed to the end, is taken from </data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a012" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a012.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a012.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a012</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.12 — Is prudence in subjects, or only in their rulers?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a012.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is in the reason. Now ruling and governing belong properly to the reason; and therefore it is proper to a man to reason and be prudent in so far as he has a share in ruling and governing. But it is evident that </data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a013" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a013.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a013.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a013</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.13 — Is prudence in the wicked?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a013.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is threefold. There is a false prudence , which takes its name from its likeness to true prudence . For since a prudent man is one who disposes well of the things that have to be done for a good end, whoever dis</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a014" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a014.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a014.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a014</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.14 — Is prudence in all good men?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a014.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The virtues must needs be connected together, so that whoever has one has all, as stated above ( I-II:65:1 ). Now whoever has grace has charity , so that he must needs have all the other virtues , and hence, since pruden</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a015" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a015.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a015.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a015</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.15 — Is prudence in us naturally?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a015.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As shown above ( Article 3 ), prudence includes knowledge both of universals, and of the singular matters of action to which prudence applies the universal principles. Accordingly, as regards the knowledge of universals,</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q047.a016" target="st.ii-ii.q047" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a016.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q047.a016.part_of.st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q047.a016</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.47 a.16 — Is prudence lost by forgetfulness?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q047</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.47 — Prudence, considered in itself</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q047.a016.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Forgetfulness regards knowledge only, wherefore one can forget art and science, so as to lose them altogether, because they belong to the reason. But prudence consists not in knowledge alone, but also in an act of the ap</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q048.a001" target="st.ii-ii.q048" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q048.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q048">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q048.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q048</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q048.a001</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.48 a.1 — The three parts of prudence: integral, subjective, and potential</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q048</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.48 — The parts of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q048.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Parts are of three kinds, namely, "integral," as wall, roof, and foundations are parts of a house; "subjective," as ox and lion are parts of animal; and " potential ," as the nutritive and sensitive powers are parts of t</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q049.a001" target="st.ii-ii.q049" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q049.a001</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.49 a.1 — Memory</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 — Each quasi-integral part of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence regards contingent matters of action, as stated above ( II-II:47:5 ). Now in such like matters a man can be directed, not by those things that are simply and necessarily true , but by those which occur in the ma</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q049.a002" target="st.ii-ii.q049" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q049.a002</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.49 a.2 — Understanding or Intelligence</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 — Each quasi-integral part of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Understanding denotes here, not the intellectual power, but the right estimate about some final principle, which is taken as self-evident: thus we are said to understand the first principles of demonstrations. Now every </data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q049.a003" target="st.ii-ii.q049" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q049.a003</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.49 a.3 — Docility</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 — Each quasi-integral part of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 2, Reply to Objection 1 ; II-II:47:3 ) prudence is concerned with particular matters of action, and since such matters are of infinite variety, no one man can consider them all sufficiently; nor</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q049.a004" target="st.ii-ii.q049" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q049.a004</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.49 a.4 — Shrewdness</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 — Each quasi-integral part of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence consists in a right estimate about matters of action. Now a right estimate or opinion is acquired in two ways, both in practical and in speculative matters, first by discovering it oneself, secondly by learning </data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q049.a005" target="st.ii-ii.q049" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a005.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a005.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q049.a005</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.49 a.5 — Reason</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 — Each quasi-integral part of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The work of prudence is to take good counsel, as stated in Ethic. vi, 7. Now counsel is a research proceeding from certain things to others. But this is the work of reason. Wherefore it is requisite for prudence that man</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q049.a006" target="st.ii-ii.q049" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a006.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a006.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q049.a006</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.49 a.6 — foresight</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 — Each quasi-integral part of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( 47, 1, ad 2, 6,13 ), prudence is properly about the means to an end, and its proper work is to set them in due order to the end. And although certain things are necessary for an end, which are subject t</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q049.a007" target="st.ii-ii.q049" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a007.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a007.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q049.a007</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.49 a.7 — Circumspection</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 — Each quasi-integral part of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 6 ), it belongs to prudence chiefly to direct something aright to an end; and this is not done aright unless both the end be good , and the means good and suitable. Since, however, prudence , as</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q049.a008" target="st.ii-ii.q049" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a008.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q049.a008.part_of.st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q049.a008</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.49 a.8 — Caution</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q049</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.49 — Each quasi-integral part of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q049.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">The things with which prudence is concerned, are contingent matters of action, wherein, even as false is found with true , so is evil mingled with good , on account of the great variety of these matters of action, wherei</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q050.a001" target="st.ii-ii.q050" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q050.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q050">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q050.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q050</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q050.a001</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.50 a.1 — Is a species of prudence regnative?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q050</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.50 — The subjective parts of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q050.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( II-II:47:10 ), it belongs to prudence to govern and command, so that wherever in human acts we find a special kind of governance and command, there must be a special kind of prudence . Now it is evident</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q050.a002" target="st.ii-ii.q050" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q050.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q050">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q050.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q050</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q050.a002</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.50 a.2 — Is political economy a species of prudence?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q050</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.50 — The subjective parts of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q050.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">A slave is moved by his master, and a subject by his ruler, by command, but otherwise than as irrational and inanimate beings are set in motion by their movers. For irrational and inanimate beings are moved only by other</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q050.a003" target="st.ii-ii.q050" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q050.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q050">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q050.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q050</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q050.a003</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.50 a.3 — Is domestic economy a species of prudence?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q050</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.50 — The subjective parts of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q050.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Different aspects of an object, in respect of universality and particularity, or of totality and partiality, diversify arts and virtues ; and in respect of such diversity one act of virtue is principal as compared with a</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q050.a004" target="st.ii-ii.q050" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q050.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q050">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q050.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q050</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q050.a004</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.50 a.4 — Is military prudence?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q050</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.50 — The subjective parts of prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q050.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Whatever things are done according to art or reason, should be made to conform to those which are in accordance with nature , and are established by the Divine Reason . Now nature has a twofold tendency: first, to govern</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q051.a001" target="st.ii-ii.q051" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q051.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q051">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q051.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q051</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q051.a001</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.51 a.1 — Is euboulia a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q051</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.51 — The virtues which are connected with prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q051.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( II-II:47:4 ) the nature of a human virtue consists in making a human act good . Now among the acts of man , it is proper to him to take counsel, since this denotes a research of the reason about the act</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q051.a002" target="st.ii-ii.q051" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q051.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q051">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q051.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q051</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q051.a002</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.51 a.2 — Is it a special virtue, distinct from prudence?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q051</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.51 — The virtues which are connected with prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q051.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 1 ), virtue is properly directed to an act which it renders good ; and consequently virtues must differ according to different acts, especially when there is a different kind of goodness in the </data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q051.a003" target="st.ii-ii.q051" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q051.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q051">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q051.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q051</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q051.a003</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.51 a.3 — Is synesis a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q051</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.51 — The virtues which are connected with prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q051.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">synesis (judging well according to common law ) signifies a right judgment, not indeed about speculative matters, but about particular practical matters, about which also is prudence . Hence in Greek some, in respect of </data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q051.a004" target="st.ii-ii.q051" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q051.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q051">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q051.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q051</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q051.a004</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.51 a.4 — Is gnome a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q051</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.51 — The virtues which are connected with prudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q051.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">cognitive habits differ according to higher and lower principles: thus in speculative matters wisdom considers higher principles than science does, and consequently is distinguished from it; and so must it be also in pra</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q052.a001" target="st.ii-ii.q052" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q052.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q052">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q052.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q052</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q052.a001</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.52 a.1 — Should counsel be reckoned among the seven gifts of the Holy Ghost?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q052</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.52 — The gift of counsel</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q052.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( I-II:68:1 ), the gifts of the Holy Ghost are dispositions whereby the soul is rendered amenable to the motion of the Holy Ghost . Now God moves everything according to the mode of the thing moved: thus </data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q052.a002" target="st.ii-ii.q052" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q052.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q052">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q052.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q052</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q052.a002</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.52 a.2 — Does the gift of counsel correspond to prudence?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q052</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.52 — The gift of counsel</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q052.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">A lower principle of movement is helped chiefly, and is perfected through being moved by a higher principle of movement, as a body through being moved by a spirit . Now it is evident that the rectitude of human reason is</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q052.a003" target="st.ii-ii.q052" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q052.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q052">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q052.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q052</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q052.a003</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.52 a.3 — Does the gift of counsel remain in heaven?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q052</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.52 — The gift of counsel</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q052.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 2 ; I-II:68:1 ), the gifts of the Holy Ghost are connected with the motion of the rational creature by God . Now we must observe two points concerning the motion of the human mind by God . First</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q052.a004" target="st.ii-ii.q052" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q052.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q052">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q052.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q052</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q052.a004</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.52 a.4 — Does the fifth beatitude, "Blessed are the merciful," etc. correspond to the gift of counsel?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q052</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.52 — The gift of counsel</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q052.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Counsel is properly about things useful for an end. Hence such things as are of most use for an end, should above all correspond to the gift of counsel. Now such is mercy, according to 1 Timothy 4:8 , " Godliness ['Pieta</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q053.a001" target="st.ii-ii.q053" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q053.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q053">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q053.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q053</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q053.a001</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.53 a.1 — Is imprudence a sin?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 — Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Imprudence may be taken in two ways, first, as a privation, secondly, as a contrary. Properly speaking it is not taken as a negation, so as merely to signify the absence of prudence , for this can be without any sin . Ta</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q053.a002" target="st.ii-ii.q053" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q053.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q053">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q053.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q053</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q053.a002</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.53 a.2 — Is it a special sin?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 — Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">A vice or sin may be styled general in two ways; first, absolutely, because, to wit, it is general in respect of all sins ; secondly, because it is general in respect of certain vices , which are its species . On the fir</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q053.a003" target="st.ii-ii.q053" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q053.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q053">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q053.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q053</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q053.a003</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.53 a.3 — Precipitation or temerity</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 — Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Precipitation is ascribed metaphorically to acts of the soul , by way of similitude to bodily movement. Now a thing is said to be precipitated as regards bodily movement, when it is brought down from above by the impulse</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q053.a004" target="st.ii-ii.q053" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q053.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q053">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q053.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q053</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q053.a004</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.53 a.4 — Thoughtlessness</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 — Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Thought signifies the act of the intellect in considering the truth about. something. Now just as research belongs to the reason, so judgment belongs to the intellect . Wherefore in speculative matters a demonstrative sc</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q053.a005" target="st.ii-ii.q053" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q053.a005.part_of.st.ii-ii.q053">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q053.a005.part_of.st.ii-ii.q053</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q053.a005</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.53 a.5 — Inconstancy</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 — Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Inconstancy denotes withdrawal from a definite good purpose. Now the origin of this withdrawal is in the appetite , for a man does not withdraw from a previous good purpose, except on account of something being inordinat</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q053.a006" target="st.ii-ii.q053" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q053.a006.part_of.st.ii-ii.q053">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q053.a006.part_of.st.ii-ii.q053</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q053.a006</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.53 a.6 — The origin of these vices</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q053</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.53 — Imprudence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q053.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As the Philosopher states (Ethic. vi, 5) "pleasure above all corrupts the estimate of prudence ," and chiefly sexual pleasure which absorbs the mind , and draws it to sensible delight. Now the perfection of prudence and </data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q054.a001" target="st.ii-ii.q054" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q054.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q054">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q054.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q054</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q054.a001</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.54 a.1 — Is negligence a special sin?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q054</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.54 — Negligence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q054.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Negligence denotes lack of due solicitude. Now every lack of a due act is sinful : wherefore it is evident that negligence is a sin , and that it must needs have the character of a special sin according as solicitude is </data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q054.a002" target="st.ii-ii.q054" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q054.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q054">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q054.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q054</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q054.a002</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.54 a.2 — To which virtue is it opposed?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q054</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.54 — Negligence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q054.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Negligence is directly opposed to solicitude. Now solicitude pertains to the reason, and rectitude of solicitude to prudence . Hence, on the other hand, negligence pertains to imprudence. This appears from its very name,</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q054.a003" target="st.ii-ii.q054" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q054.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q054">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q054.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q054</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q054.a003</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.54 a.3 — Is negligence a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q054</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.54 — Negligence</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q054.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 2, Reply to Objection 3 ), negligence arises out of a certain remissness of the will , the result being a lack of solicitude on the part of the reason in commanding what it should command, or as</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q055.a001" target="st.ii-ii.q055" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a001.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q055.a001</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.55 a.1 — Is prudence of the flesh a sin?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 — Vices opposed to prudence by way of resemblance</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( II-II:47:13 ), prudence regards things which are directed to the end of life as a whole. Hence prudence of the flesh signifies properly the prudence of a man who looks upon carnal goods as the last end </data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q055.a002" target="st.ii-ii.q055" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a002.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q055.a002</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.55 a.2 — Is it a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 — Vices opposed to prudence by way of resemblance</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( II-II:47:2 ad 1 ; Article 13 ), a man is said to be prudent in two ways. First, simply, i.e. in relation to the end of life as a whole. Secondly, relatively, i.e. in relation to some particular end; thu</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q055.a003" target="st.ii-ii.q055" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a003.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q055.a003</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.55 a.3 — Is craftiness a special sin?</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 — Vices opposed to prudence by way of resemblance</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Prudence is "right reason applied to action," just as science is "right reason applied to knowledge ." On speculative matters one may sin against rectitude of knowledge in two ways: in one way when the reason is led to a</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q055.a004" target="st.ii-ii.q055" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a004.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q055.a004</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.55 a.4 — Guile</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 — Vices opposed to prudence by way of resemblance</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">As stated above ( Article 3 ), it belongs to craftiness to adopt ways that are not true but counterfeit and apparently true , in order to attain some end either good or evil . Now the adopting of such ways may be subject</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q055.a005" target="st.ii-ii.q055" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a005.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a005.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q055.a005</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.55 a.5 — Fraud</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 — Vices opposed to prudence by way of resemblance</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Just as "guile" consists in the execution of craftiness, so also does " fraud ." But they seem to differ in the fact that "guile" belongs in general to the execution of craftiness, whether this be effected by words, or b</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q055.a006" target="st.ii-ii.q055" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a006.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a006.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q055.a006</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.55 a.6 — Solicitude about temporal things</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
  <data key="d11">part_of</data>
  <data key="d12">st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d13">II-II q.55 — Vices opposed to prudence by way of resemblance</data>
  <data key="d14">question</data>
  <data key="d15"></data>
  <data key="d16">st.ii-ii.q055.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d17">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d18">Solicitude denotes an earnest endeavor to obtain something. Now it is evident that the endeavor is more earnest when there is fear of failure, so that there is less solicitude when success is assured. Accordingly solicit</data>
  <data key="d19">structural</data>
  <data key="d20"></data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q055.a007" target="st.ii-ii.q055" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a007.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055">
  <data key="d7">structural.st.ii-ii.q055.a007.part_of.st.ii-ii.q055</data>
  <data key="d8">st.ii-ii.q055.a007</data>
  <data key="d9">II-II q.55 a.7 — Solicitude about the future</data>
  <data key="d10">article</data>
